{"title_page": "St Edmund's School Canterbury", "text_new": "{{redirect|St Edmund's School}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = St Edmund's School, Canterbury\n| image         = St Edmund's School.svg\n| caption       = \n| image_size          = 150px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.2917|1.0597|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = [[Latin]]: \"Fungar Vice Cotis\"<br/>(Be as a whetstone for others to be sharpened upon)\n| established   = 1749\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Public school (United Kingdom)|Public school]] <br /> [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|Independent]] <br />[[day school|day]] and [[boarding school]]\n| religious_affiliation      = [[Church of England]]\n| president     = \n| head_label    = Head\n| head          = Edward O\u2019Connor\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   =Chairman of Governors \n| chair         =Air Marshal C.M. Nickols, CB, CBE, MA, FRAeS \n| founder       = \n| specialist    = \n| address        = St Thomas' Hill\n| city          = [[Canterbury]]\n| county        = [[Kent]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = CT2 8HU\n| local_authority           = Kent\n| ofsted        = \n| urn       = 118998\n| staff         = \n| enrolment    = 570\n| gender        = Coeducational\n| lower_age     = 3\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       =Red & Black {{color box|red}} {{color box|black}} \n| publication   = \n| website       = www.stedmunds.org.uk\n|free_1=[[:Category:People educated at St Edmund's School, Canterbury|Old Edmundians]]|free_label_1=Former pupils|free_2=\"The Chronicle\"|free_label_2=Yearbook}}\n'''St Edmund's School, Canterbury''' is an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] day and [[boarding school]] located in [[Canterbury, Kent]], England and established in 1749. The extensive school grounds were acquired in 1855. The school currently caters for girls and boys aged 3\u201318, including the Choristers of [[Canterbury Cathedral]].\n\nThe School is currently headed by Edward O\u2019Connor and is part of the [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]. Senior School (ages 13\u201318) boarding fees for the academic year 2019/20 are \u00a336,881 per annum and \u00a321,132 for day pupils. The school is among the most expensive conference schools in the UK. Theyre star pupils are Seamus Soutar \n\n== History ==\nSt Edmund's School Canterbury was first established in 1749, as the Clergy Orphan Society (later the [[Clergy Orphan Corporation]]) in [[Yorkshire]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}} In 1812, the school moved to [[St John's Wood]] at the nursery end of [[Lord's Cricket Ground]]. An associated school for girls was located on the same site, but later moved to become [[St Margaret's School, Bushey]], in [[Hertfordshire]].\n[[File:St Edmunds School Canterbury2.jpg|thumb|St. Edmund's School facade]]\nIn 1855, the school moved to [[Canterbury]]. The acquisition of property and financing to build the school was provided by [[Samuel Wilson Warneford]]. The main school building was designed by [[Philip Charles Hardwick]] architect of [[Charterhouse School]] and [[Adare Manor]]. The [[chapel]] wing of the school was completed in 1858 and remains in daily use.\n\nThe choristers of Canterbury Cathedral began their education at the school in 1972. Grant house was established from the former Big School, after 20 years the school reverted to the traditional 4 house system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stedmunds.org.uk/about-us/history/|title=History \u2013 St Edmund's School Canterbury|website=www.stedmunds.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-02-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, girls were admitted to the school for the first time.<ref>{{cite book|title=Foundation on a Hill by Jock Asbury-Bailey|url=http://www.stedmunds.org.uk/about-us/history/}}</ref>\n\nA teacher was awarded damages and compensation after wrongful and unfair dismissal by the school in 2010.<ref>http://www.kentonline.co.uk/canterbury/news/teacher-wins-40000-payout-after-1192/</ref>\n\nIn 2016 the school was fined \u00a318000 and ordered to pay costs of \u00a39670, after a seven-year-old child nearly drowned at the Summerfest event held at the school. The school did not ensure the lifeguards held the relevant qualifications, it could not be sure the guards had any experience or competency.<ref>http://www.kentonline.co.uk/canterbury/news/boy-7-nearly-drowns-at-102467/</ref>\n\nThe [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] is the school\u2019s patron.\n\n[[File:1st photo 1889.tif|thumb|1st photo of the School 1889]]\n\n== Facilities ==\n[[File:St Edmund's School West Dormitory 1880.tif|thumb|St Edmund's School West Dormitory 1880]]\nThe main building houses classrooms, boarding facilities, dining hall, library and administration offices.  Further buildings provide teaching areas for Art, Design Technology and Science. The Francis Musgrave Performing Arts Center comprises a purpose-built music school with recording studio, practice rooms and recital hall. There is also a 450-seat theater for concerts and drama productions.\n\nSports facilities include sports hall, gym, all-weather astro pitch, golf course, playing fields, 8 tennis courts, shooting range and swimming pool. Additional boarding houses are set in the grounds of the school.\n\nThe Junior School and Pre-Prep School are located on the same site in their own buildings.\n[[File:Stedmunds 300715 1871 crop.jpg|thumb]]\n\n== Houses ==\nThe Senior School is divided into four day houses:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Named After \n|-\n|Baker||  Baker. A Victorian benefactor of the school \n|-\n|Wagner||  Wagner. A Victorian benefactor of the school\n|-\n|Warneford|| Dr. Samuel Warneford. A Victorian benefactor of the school, who donated the site and the building of the current location in Canterbury. \n|-\n|Watson|| Watson. A Victorian benefactor of the school \n|}\nIn Junior School there are four houses: \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Named After \n|-\n|Becket||  [[Thomas Becket]] \n|-\n|Chaucer||  [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]\n|-\n|Marlowe|| [[Christopher Marlowe]]\n|-\n|Roper|| [[William Roper]] \n|}\nThe boarding houses:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Named After \n|-\n|Owen (Senior School)||  Owen. A benefactor of the school \n|-\n|School House (Junior School)||  N/A\n|}\n\n== Cathedral choir ==\nIn 1972, the previously independent Canterbury Cathedral Choir School, which educated the choristers of Canterbury Cathedral, joined the Junior School as the Choir House. Choir House remains at a detached location beside the cathedral, and provided transport conveys the choirboys between the two sites.\n\n== Heads ==\n*The name of the first Headmaster, between the years 1751 and 1762, is unknown.\n*The Revd Daniel Addison (1762 \u2013 1783)\n*The Revd Daniel Addison (1783 \u2013 1804)\n*The Revd Thomas Cripps (1804 \u2013 1805)\n*The Revd Evan Jones (1805 \u2013 1813)\n*The Revd William Farley (1813 \u2013 1816)\n*The Revd Thomas Wharton (1817 \u2013 1837)\n*The Revd George Bewsher (1837 \u2013 1841)\n*The Revd. Daniel Butler (1841 \u2013 1867)\n*The Revd Charles Matheson (1867 \u2013 1891)\n*The Revd Arthur W. Upcott (1891 \u2013 1902)\n*The Revd Edward J.W. Houghton (1902 \u2013 1908)\n*The Revd Walter F. Burnside (1908 \u2013 1932)\n*The Revd Henry Balmforth (1932 \u2013 1941)\n*The Revd Frederick F.S. Williams (1942 \u2013 1945)\n*William M. Thoseby (1945 \u2013 1959)\n*Walter Stephen Jones (1 term 1959)\n*[[Michael Hoban|B. Michael S.Hoban]] (1960 \u2013 1964)\n*Francis R. Rawes (1964 \u2013 1978)\n*John V. Tyson (1978 \u2013 1994)\n*A. Nicholas Ridley (1994 \u2013 2005)\n*Jeremy M. Gladwin (2005 \u2013 2011)\n*Louise J. Moelwyn-Hughes (2011 \u2013 2018)\n*Edward O'Connor (2018 \u2013 )<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcement of New Head for September 2018 |url=http://www.stedmunds.org.uk/news/2017/11/announcement-of-new-head-for-sept-2018/ |website=St Edmund's School |accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reviews ==\nThe Good Schools Guide note that after the schools' rebranding it was no longer marketing itself as a music and drama school, nor did it continue to describe itself as \"non-selective\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Good Schools Guide|url=https://www.goodschoolsguide.co.uk/schools/103626/st-edmund-s-school}}</ref>\n\nThe Independent Schools Inspectorate reported in 2015 that the school met all the requirements of the Education (Independent School Standards) Regulations.<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 ISI Inspection report|url=http://www.isi.net/school/st-edmund-s-school-canterbury-6956}}</ref>\n\n== Notable former pupils ==\n{{See also|Category:People educated at St Edmund's School, Canterbury}}\n\nFormer pupils are granted membership to St Edmund's Society.\n\n*[[Benjamin Handley Geary|Benjamin Handley Geary VC]], Victoria Cross Recipient\n*[[Orlando Bloom]], Actor\n*[[Stuart Townend (headmaster)|Stuart Townend]], Athlete, soldier and schoolmaster\n*[[Dan Caplen]], Musician\n*[[Willoughby Allen]], Priest\n*[[Jon Baddeley]], Auctioneer\n*[[Thomas Crick]], Anglican priest\n*[[Lawrence Durrell]], Novelist\n*[[Darren Henley]], Chief Executive of Arts Council England\n*[[Hope Gill]], Anglican bishop\n*[[Michael Goodliffe]], Actor\n*[[Sanjeev Gupta]], Industrialist\n*[[Bernard Howlett]], Soldier\n*[[Geoffrey Iliff]], Anglican bishop\n*[[Robin Jackman]], Cricketer\n*[[Freddy Kempf]], Pianist\n*[[Tom London (magician)|Tom London]], Magician and hacker\n*[[John Long (priest)|John Long]], Priest\n*[[Arthur Lovekin]], Journalist and politician\n*[[Nigel MacArthur]], Broadcaster\n*[[Gordon MacMillan (British Army officer)|Sir Gordon MacMillan]], British Army General\n*[[Chris Nickols]], Royal Air Force Officer\n*[[Alan Payne]], Cricketer\n*[[John Peacey]], Cricketer\n*[[John Pinsent]], Classicist\n*[[Roger Royle]], Priest and broadcaster\n*[[Hedley Sparks]], Anglican priest and academic\n*[[Max Spiers]], Conspiracy theorist{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n*[[Mark Strudwick]], Soldier\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://www.goodschoolsguide.co.uk/schools/103626/st-edmund-s-school/31fef69#sch_tabs-2/ Good Schools Guide]\n* [https://www.canterbury-cathedral.org/worship/choir/choristers-2/ Choristers of Canterbury Cathedral]\n\n{{Schools in Kent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Edmund's School}}\n[[Category:Independent schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Edmund's School, Canterbury| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Schools in Canterbury]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1740s]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:1749 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|St Edmund's School}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = St Edmund's School, Canterbury\n| image         = St Edmund's School.svg\n| caption       = \n| image_size          = 150px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.2917|1.0597|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = [[Latin]]: \"Fungar Vice Cotis\"<br/>(Be as a whetstone for others to be sharpened upon)\n| established   = 1749\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Public school (United Kingdom)|Public school]] <br /> [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|Independent]] <br />[[day school|day]] and [[boarding school]]\n| religious_affiliation      = [[Church of England]]\n| president     = \n| head_label    = Head\n| head          = Edward O\u2019Connor\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   =Chairman of Governors \n| chair         =Air Marshal C.M. Nickols, CB, CBE, MA, FRAeS \n| founder       = \n| specialist    = \n| address        = St Thomas' Hill\n| city          = [[Canterbury]]\n| county        = [[Kent]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = CT2 8H